{"/service/ndnp/nvln/batch_nvln_deeth_ver01/data/sn86076247/00332890487/1920061001/0965.xml":{"full_text":"THE SILVER STATE\n1 THREE-TIMES-A-WEEK\u2014TUESDAY, THURSDAY, SATURDAY ESTABLISHED Mt\u00bb ALL THE NEWS OF HUMBOLDT COUNTY AND TRADING TeSmITORY\n5f PER COPY-SLOP PER YEAR _WINNEMUCCA, NEVADA, THURSDAY, JUNE 10, 1920 VOLUME AS. N* 144\nNEVADA DELEGATE\nSIZES UP GWCACO\n\n\"Anything is liable to happen.\u201d is\nthe way Sam Platt, who is one of\nNevada's delegates to the Republi\ncan national convention, now in prog\nress at Chicago, sums up the situa\ntion. Rumors of a \"dark horse\u201d be\ning successful are rife, he says, in\na dispatch to the Reno Gazette, which\nfollows:\nOn the event of the day set aside\nfor nominating speeches delegates to\nthe national convention and those\nwho are not delegates and are on the\n\"inside\" are all at sea as to the prob\nable nominee. The situation is cloud\nier than ever. The latest possible au\nthentic rumor is that the senatorial\n\"old guard\u201d ultimately will control\nthe situation. This means that trad\ning is in progress to select a nominee\nfree from the stigma of slush funds,\na good vote getter and an ardent Re\npublican with enough progressive\nness to unite all factions. There is\na persistent belief that only a \u201cdark\nhorse\u201d will meet the requirements\nwith Governor Sproule of Pennsyl\nvania and Charles K. Huges most\nprominently mentioned.\nAnother inside story is that among\nthe prominent contenders Senator\nHarding is strongest and Anally will\nwin. I have talked with leaders and\nveteran newspaper men who are all\nnuzzled\nIt la certain that up to this time no\ndefinite forecast may be made. Re\nliable sources have given out the in\nformation that tickets are being\nprinted for next week. This means\na deadlock and a protracted fight un\nless conditions settle in a day or so\nThe fight on the League of Nations\nplatform plank will begin tomorrow\nheaded by Johnson and Borah, both\nJohnson s chances, eliminate him al\ntogether or stampede the convention\nfor some brilliant campaign orator\nAnything is liable to happen.\nC THREE CONVICTS ESCAPED\nFROM PRISON YESTERDAY\nLiOcal authorities received a tele\ngram last night that three convicts\nbad escaped from the state peniten\ntiary at 5 p.m. yesterday. They were\nArthur Henderson, 22, sent up from\nthis county to serve a l-to-15 year\nterm for robbing the E. Reinhart com\npany store at Golconda; Olen Turner\n27, from Elko for forgery, l-to-14\nyears; and Ted* Ryan. 29. sent from\nWashoe county April 26 of this year\nto serve a l-to-14 yea r term for\nforgery.\nTO ATTEND* CAMP MEETING\nMrs. F. A. Kail expects to leave\nSaturday for Reno to attend the ses\nsions of the Adventist camp meeting\nwhich closes on the 20th of June. She\nwill afterwards spend an indefinite\ntime in Fallon visiting with relatives\nLAND FILINGS\nL. O. Hawkins has made application\nbefore County Clerk Davey for a sec\ntlon of land, located near Pronto. Thr\nfiling was made under the Pittman\nact.\nm\nAll white help at the Star Cafe\nEat here once and you'll return. Adv\nRegular\nPrices\nOn Quality Goods\nBlue Ribbon Peeled\nDried Peaches\ntlk cartons.-$1.50\nMull packages-25*\nFBEB DELfTEBT TO\nAET PART OF THE CITY\nWinnemucca\nMercantile Co.\nREPUBLICANS AT CHICAGO COMMENCING\nTO GET ACTION; PUTFORM BROUGHT IN\nFollowing are telegrams received\nby The Silver State from time to\ntime concerning the activities at the\nRepublican convention at Chicago.\nTomorrow and on other off-publica\ntion days as long as the convention\nlasts, these bulletins will be posted\nin front of The Silver State office.\nPlatform Kraft Complete\nCONVENTION HALL. CHICAGO,\nJune 10 (11:13 a.m ).\u2014Senator Mc\nCormick of Illinois reported from\nCommittee on Resolutions that the\ncommittee had been working many\nhours and had agreed on platform, in\ncluding plank concerning the League\nof Nations. Loud cheers greeted the\nannouncement.\nRecess to Study Platform\n11:35 a.m. Senator McCormick\nmoved that the convention recess un\ntil 4 p.ra., so that the delegates could\nstudy the platform to be submitted by\nthe committee. A rising vote was\nnecessary because of loud opposition,\nbut the motion to recess Anally was\ncarried.\nNational Committeemen Named\n4:44 p.m.\u2014A list of names of men\nwho will make up the new Republican\nNational Committee was announced.\n(In this list the name of George\nWingAeld was undoubtedly announced\nas national committeeman from Ne\nvada.\nSherman of Illinois Cheered\n4:46 p.m.\u2014The name of Senator\nSherman of Illinois was greeted with\nloud applause.\nI'ncle Joe Cannon Called\n4:57 p.m.\u2014Uncle Joe Cannon was\ncalled for and greeted with loud and\nlong cheering, all delegates rising.\nINK WOOL WILL\nRECOVER IN PRICE\nDespite discouraging reports con\ncerning the future wool market, cer\ntain facts are being brought out that\ngive strength to the hope that the\nmarket will return to the sixty-cent\nbasis from which it recently receded.\nMany and conflicting are the opinions\nconcerning the wool market, finan\ncial affairs and business outlook for\nthe United States. Private advice has\nbeen received in Winnemucca from\nmen interested in wool stating that\nthey look for the market to recover\nwithin the next three weeks.\nA special report of conditions affect\ning values, sent out from the Wash\nington Woolen Mills Company, is in\nteresting and follows:\n\"Recent developments in our in\nlustry have been so radical that we\nfeel that our views in the form of a\nspecial report might be appreciated.\n\"We are going through a form of\nhysteria in the liquidation of mer\nchandise through forced sales and\n(Continued on Page Four)\nWIN X EM H A'S AlttPLAN E\nFIELD READY FOR I\u2019LAXES\nWith completion today of a \"pig\"\u2014\nhe latest method of \u201cmarking\" an\niviation landing field\u2014Winnemucca\u2019s\nacilities for birdmen and their planes\nan truthfully be said to compare\nvith landing fields in other cities.\nThe final touch will be accomplished\nwhen a large \"W,\u201d thirty feet long, is\ntainted on the ground. But to ex\nplain the \"pig\" business\u2014lit is a\nvooden hoop fitted to a rod so that\nt will revolve. Attached to it is a\npiece of linen twenty feet long, cone\nshaped. When the wind blows this\none fills with air and furnishes an\nasily discernable mark for an avia\ntor and indicates to him in which di\nrection the wind is blowing.\nLARD AXD HAMS\nThe Winnemucca Market is making\ni special of lard at thirty cents per\ntound. guaranteed class one. Picnic\niams at the same old price of twenty\nMx cents per pound. Advt.\nWe take particular pride in the\noffee we serve at the Star Cafe. Adv.\nIMIAY MAI FOUND\nEM OF ASSAULT\nE. J. Thacker of Imlay was found\nj guilty of assault and ordered to pay\nI $750 damages and costs to Martin\nDells by the Lovelock court Tuesday,\naccording to the Reno Gazette.\nOn the evening of August 10, 1918,\nMartin Dells, a miner, was cutting\nacross Thacker's field headed for\nImlay. when Thacker came along in\nhis car and jumped out and attacked\nDells in which .Dells claims, he was\nknocked down and kicked. It was\nin front of the car in the same di\nrection he came.\nThacker was charged with assault\nand battery on August 18 by Dells\nand found guilty in the justice court\nof both charges.\nI^ater, in an appeal, Thacker was\nagain found guilty in the district\ncourt, but only of assault. The case\nwas again appealed to jury session\nof the district court in which Thacker\nwas again found guilty of assault.\nThis is the last jury case for the\nsession of the district. Judge Calla\nhan heard several civil cases yester\nday.\nLOCAL M AX ELECTED CASHIER\nOF NEW EUREKA BANK\nC. J. Travers, who for the past four\nyears has held a position with the\nWinnemucca State Bank Trust\nj company of this city, has been elected\ncashier of the Farmers\u2019 and Mer\nchants\u2019 'Bank of Eureka, a new or\nganized institution. The election of\nofficers was held at Eureka the first\npart of the week and resulted as fol\nlows: J. Sheehan, president; J. A.\nBiale. vice-president; Walter Hand\nley. vice-president, and C. J. Travers,\ncashier. The new institution will\nopen for business about July 1.\nTravers will leave the latter part\nof this month to assume his new re\nsponsibilities.\nHENDERSON IS ON HIS WAY\nFROM W ASHINGTON TO NEVADA\nSenator Henderson has left Wash\nington, D. C., and is on his way home\nHe will stop off in Chicago to see\nhow the Republicans conduct a na\ntional convention, when he will come\non home, arriving about the latter\nj part of the week.\u2014[Free Press.\nChickens\nYear-olds and\nSpring Friers\n\ni\n\nRaised Locally\nSupply Limited\nTHE PURITY STORE\nPHONE 421\n_r__-\nStraw\nHats\nWe l.ave a complete line\not Crofut Knapp Straw\nand Panama Hats. The\nstyle is new and the price\nis right\nOliverius Minor\n\u201cETerjthiig For Mob\"\nr\nRENO. June Aerial broncho i\nbusting is the latest in the way of\nsensational stunts in connection with\nrodeos. It will be on display for the\nfirst time at the Reno rodeo, to be\nheld July 2nd to 5th, inclusive.\nFranklin Rose, the world's great\nest dare-devil, has defied Pilot Cloyd\nClevenger to dismount him from a\nsaddle which will be rigged half be\ntween the cock-pit and rudder of the\nVarney Lincoln standard plane.\nClevenger will go through all of\nthe antics in the air that such fa\nmous outlaw horses as Misky, Mix,\nSakgway, Mascot, Moving Picture.\nGrass Valley and Wild Cat perform\non the ground.\nPilot Clevenger claims that his\nVarney Lincoln stand.\u201dcan out\nbuck any broncho fnat will perform\non the Reno field. Rose admits that\nhe could not sit on the broncho for\nthirty* seconds, but that Clevenger\ncannot unseat him in thirty minutes\nof aerial antics.\nFranklin Rose has become famous\nfor many daring exhibitions in the\npast. He is the only air dare-devil\nwho has attempted and succeeded in\nlooping the loop while hanging from\nthe Landing nf n ni\u00bbno Pnua\ndoes wing-walking, ladder trapeze\nwork, and gained much fame by\njumping from a motorcycle to an air\nplane and from a locomotive to a\nplane.\nIn addition to the program of thril\nling events provided by Rose, Pilot\nCloyd Clevenger announces aerial ac\nrobatics that have never before been\nattempted at the high altitude of\nReno. Clevenger is perhaps the most\nsensational pilot on the Coast. In\na competition held at Redwood City,\nCalifornia, May 1, in which forty pi\nlots participated. Clevenger was\nawarded the championship trophy as\nthe Coast\u2019s most expert Stuntist.\nManager Glenn Hurst has arranged\nwith Clevenger to carry passengers\nin bis three passenger plane during\nthe entire progress of the rodeo. In\norder to accommodate passengft-s\nHurst will operate a special line of\nautos between the rodeo field and the\nflying field.\nWESTERN PACIFIC PRESIDENT\nWAS WINNEMCCCA VISITOR\nC. M. Levy, president of the West\nern Pacific railroad, accompanied by\nT. J. Wyatch. chief engineer, and Mr.\nBaldwin, receiver for the Rio Grande,\nwere visitors here Tuesday on a tour\nof inspection from Wells to Winne\nmucca. While here they looked over\ncompany property and attended to\nother business. In railroad circles\nhere it is pretty well talked that this\nvisit is part of President Levy\u2019s plan\nto secure adjustment for damage to\nthe W.P. during government control,\nhis efforts so far, it is said, having\nresulted in the payment of three mil\nlion dollars by the Southern Pacific.\nIt is thought this trip is for the pur\npose of determining loss sustained by\nthe W.P. by reason of the double\ntrack scheme in force during the war\nunder which trains of both roads\nused the S.P. track for western traf\nfic and W.P. track for eastern, be\ntween this city and Wendover. It is\nunderstood an additional million dol\nlars will be demanded from the S.P.\nfor damage to W.P. track by reason\nof heavier traffic.\nCHAUTArQFA DIRECTOR IS\nMAJOR IN FRENCH ARMY\nA. F. Paulmer, who will direct Win\nnemucca\u2019s Chautauqua, arrived here\ny* sterday. He will be In direct\ncharge from the time the tents open\nnext Saturday afternoon until the\n(Inal attraction is over a week from\nnext Friday night. Mr. Palmer has\nrecently returned from overseas,\nwhere he was an interpreter during\nthe war for the Fifth French army.\nHe was wounded and gassed during\nthe last few months of fighting and\nfor various acts was named an honor\nary major in the French army and\nliberally present*d with medals.\nBAR SILVER DROPS\nBar silver made another violent de\ncline in the New York market this\nweek, falling about ten to eighty-four\ncents an ounce.\nDAIRY FOR SALE\nOnly Winnemucca dairy business\nfor sale, with all equipment and\nthirty-two head of Holstein cows. Or\nwill sell cows separately.\nAdvUlOtf BOHNERT BROS.\nRENO EUR COMING:\nHERE JULY TENTH\nI\nS' The Elks are coming Saturday. j\nJuly 10. This was the message i\nreceived here yesterday from\nExalted Ruler French of Reno\nLodge, B.P.O.E., of which most\nElks in Winnemucca are mem-\nbers. New names are being\nadded to list of candidates to be <S>\nInitiated here at that time and\nit is plhnned by Winnemucca\nElks to provide entertainment\nfor them of a nature they will\nnot likely forget.\nAt first it was thought the\nReno officers and members\nwould come here the middle or\nlast of this month, but the date\nV was left open so that the best\ndate possible could be selected\nto secure complete success of\nthe occasion. The trouble with\nthe tentative dates set of June\n19 and 26 is that they conflict\nwith other perhaps more itnpor\n<6> tant events. On June 19 a spe- <es\ndal trainload of Shriners will j\nleave Reno for the Portland con-\nvention. Most of the members <3>\nof that order are Elks and thus <f>\ncould not attend Winnemucca\u2019s\nw blow-out. On July 5 the Reno\nRodeo will conflict. Therefore\nTill V 1 AtVl la tlto m oat aniinkln\ndate. All of this is explained be- <8\ncause of impatience manifested <8>\nV here, some people postponing va-\ncations to lie sure to be here for\nthe Elks\u2019 event.\nThat the committee of local\nElks in charge intends to \"go\nright to the bat\" is indicated by <8\na committee meeting call for to- <8\n\u25a08 morrow night at 8:30. to be held <8\n4> in the Winnemucca State Bank. 8\nWinnemucca Elks have already <8\n<8 instructed this committee to\n<8 spare no expense or effort to <8\n8 make the initiation something to\nbe remembered. And a prelimi- <8\nnary report of the amount of 8\n8 money to be spent is staggering.\n\u20228 Correspondence is to be taken\n'8 up with the Elko Stray Elks \u201d8\n*8 lodge to get them to renew the <t\n\u20228 promise of two of their members 8\nthat \u201cat least a special car\u201d of <8\nElks and ladies will come to the <8\n\u20228 Winnemucca initiation. Reports <8\n<8 are that Lovelock will send a\n8 typical, large, full-of-pep delega- 8\n<8 tion, and many other Elks from <8\n<8 other places are expected to be 8 I\n<8 in attendance, in addition to the 8 I\n<8 big representation from Reno. \u20188\n<8 Inquiries have been received as 8\n<8 far away as Ogden. 8\n8 Altogether it looks like a big 8\n<8\u201c day for Winnemucca. with the 8 i\n8 Elks ball that night creating the 8\n8 greatest interest among towns-\n8 people. *8\n88888888888888888\n\nTHIRD GAME WITH LOVELOCK\nTO BE PLAYED HERE SUNDAY\nThere will be a return game of\nbaseball played at Recreation Park\nnext Sunday afternoon between Love\nlock and Winnemucca. This will be\nthe third contest between the two\nnines. Lovelock having won both of j\nthe previous matches. Free auto\nconveyance will be furnished to and\nfrom the game and it is hoped to see\nthe grand stand packed with fans\nto help root the local boys to a\nvictory.\nTEACHERS\u2019 EXAMINATIONS\nAn examination of applicants for\nteachers' certificates will be held\nat the Winnemucca grammar school\nbuilding beginning Monday, June 14,,\nat 9 a.m. Applicants must furnish\nwriting material.\nAd.jel0-t2 MRS. JENNIE SMITH.\nCLUB MEETING\nThe regular meeting of the Fort\nnightly club will be held tomorrow\nevening, June 11, at Parish hall.\nEverybody invited.\nDIRECTORS\u2019 MEETING\nThe regular monthly meeting of\nFirst National Bank directors was\nheld today, Messrs. Sheehan, Doyle,\nStall and Stock being in attendance.\nPROMPT SERVICE AND\nFIRST-CLASS WORK\n\u2014In Kodak developing and printing\nAll work done at our stoi a No more j\nlong tiresome waits for your pictures.\n\u2014[Advt EAGLE DRUG CO.\n____________\nThe best the market affords is reg\nularly served at the Star Cafe. Adv.\nPETER PEDROU DIES\nTESTERDAT AT RERB\nFollowing an operation for Hi\nstones, performed at a Reno hospital,\nfrom which he failed to rally, Peter\nPedroll of this city, paseed away yes\nterday morning. Pedroll had been a\nresident of Winnemucca for more\nthan thirty years and enjoyed the\nconfidence and respect of the entire\ncommunity. He had gone to Reno\na short time ago, accompanied by bis\nwife, in an effort to benefit his health,\nand it was first thought he would\ncompletely recover, but a relapse oc\ncurred and his condition steadily\ngrew worse. Mrs. Pedroll was with\nher husband at the end.\nDeceased was forty-eight years old\nand a native of Switzerland, having\narrived in this state thirty-five years\nago and engaged in ranching about\ntwelve miles from this city, later re\nmoving to Winnemucca. At the time\nof his death he was janitor of the\ncourt house.\nThe remains, accompanied by Mrs.\nPedroll, arrived in this city this\nmorning and may be viewed at the\nfamily residence in West First street,\nbetween the hours of eight and nine\no\u2019clock Saturday morning.\nFuneral arrangements are under\nthe direction of Undertaker Carlson\nand will be held from the Catholic\nchurch. Saturdav niorninr at ten\no\u2019clock, Father Meisekothen officiat\ning. The pall bearers will be as fol\nlows: Albert Seeliger, J. W. Davey.\nThomas Powell, George Creek, Frank\nGermain and William Spinner.\nPRODUCTION OF GRAIN SHOWS\nINCREASE OVER LAST TEAR\nMay was rather favorable for crop\ngrowth in Nevada. The greatest\nchange in condition was in pasture\nand range which rose from seventy\ntwo to ninety per cent.\nThe production of grain will prob\nably be greater than last year. The\ngreatest increase will be in parts re\nflecting the more favorable outlook\nin Elko county. A prospective water\nshortage on th? lower Humboytt has\ncaused a reduction in the acreage\nof grain in that section. This was\nmade up in other sections so that the\nstate totals were not affected. An\nother slight increase in alfalfa acre\nage occurred this year. The condi\ntion of hay is slightly below average,\nbut a fair crop is forecast.\nThe condition of truck and vege\ntables is generally good. Fruits are\nconsiderably better than average.\nWEATHER REPORT\nFor the twenty-four hours ended at\n8 a.m. today:\nHighest temperature yesterday, 79.\nLowest this morning, 49.\n.Mean temperature yesterday, 64.\nNormal temperature yesterday, 61.\nRel. humidity 5 p.m. yesterday, 21.\nRel. humidity 5 a.m. today, 43.\nWeather forecast for the twenty\nfour hours ending 5 p.m. tomorrow:\nFair tonight and Friday.\nMrs. Ethel Kibbee, who spent a\nday or two In Carson as the guest of\nher sister-in-law', Mrs. Edward Cur\nran, has gone to San Francisco. Mrs.\nKibbee is a teacher in the Winne\nmucca schools.\u2014[Carson News.\nDependable\nElectrical Work\nDone by an electrical bouse\nis a satisfaction as well as\na safeguard. Give us a trial\nREPAIR WORK OF ALL KINDS\nIS PROMPTLY ATTENDED TO\nAgents for Westinghouse Mazda\nLamps, Hughes and Hot-Point\nappliances, Electric Ranges, etc.\nHOUSE WIRING FIXTURES\nMOTOR INSTALLATIONS, ETC.\nPhones:\u2014Res. K52; Shop, 871\nWinnemucca\nElectric Co.\nBox 431 Wianemucca, Nor. II\n\u2014M","height":"28728","width":"20000"}}
